ce:section.ce:para:
The morphology of FA, 18P–C, P–C-dots@FA, and P–C-dots@FA/18P–C were observed using scanning electron microscopy (Fig. 1
                        ) and TEM (Fig. 2
                        ). FA (Fig. 1(a)) exhibited a typical spherical structure with diameters ranging from a few microns to hundreds of nanometers. Meanwhile, 18P–C (Fig. 1(b)) had a lamellar structure with a carbon layer attached to the P–C-dots@FA surface (Fig. 1(c)), which can also be observed in the P–C-dots@FA/18P–C composite (Fig. 1(d)). In particular, FA exhibited an uneven spherical carbon distribution on the lamellar surface of the phosphorylated carbon, which promoted the photocatalyst properties of FA. Moreover, all four materials did not exhibit an obvious pore structure. The BET characterization noted the smaller specific surface area and pore volume of the carbon-containing materials P–C-dots@FA and P–C-dots@FA/18P–C, which further confirmed their morphological characteristics (Fig. S1).
